<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-418-549  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 418 549.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  July 5 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Dow Jones, DataTimes join forces. (Dow Jones News/Retrieval)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Buckler, Grant.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dow Jones and Company Inc. (contracts)Oklahoma Publishing Co. (contracts).andO;Topic:     Dow Jones News-Retrieval (Information retrieval system)DataTimes (Information storage and retrieval system)On-LineInformation Storage and Retrieval.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DOW JONES, DATATIMES JOIN FORCES PRINCETON, NEW JERSEY, U.S.A., 1990 JUL 2(NB) -- Operators of the Dow Jones News/Retrieval and DataTimes onlineinformation services have brought their services together on one system, sosubscribers to each service have access to the combined resources of both.andM;Subscribers will now be able to search more than 500 domestic andinternational newspapers, magazines, trade journals and wire services, thecompanies said.andP;  However, each service will retain its own user interface.andO;&quot;The common features will be the publications,&quot; Alyce Perkins, a spokeswomanfor Dow Jones, told Newsbytes.andM;&quot;At this point,&quot; added Wes Crews, product services manager at DataTimes inOklahoma, &quot;we're still simply two different and autonomous services.&quot;andM;Dow Jones bought 15 percent of DataTimes last year from The OklahomaPublishing Co., which still owns the balance of Datatimes as well as TheDaily and Sunday Oklahoman in Oklahoma City, Gaylord Broadcasting Company,Opryland U.S.A.andP;  and the Nashville Network.andM;Crews would not rule out the possibility the two services could mergeentirely some day, but Perkins said that is not in the cards.andP;  The twoservices will share data and both will work to make their facilities easierto use, she said.andP;  &quot;They're very much an independent company,&quot; Perkins saidof DataTimes.andM;Perkins said Dow Jones' major target markets include large businesses,professional researchers and individual users.andP;  Crews said DataTimes focuseson vertical markets such as legal firms, media, public relations andacademia.andM;The shared system will let customers of both services search by publicationsaccording to region, circulation size and publication type.andP;  For example, acustomer seeking information from newspapers and magazines in the easternUnited States carried by DataTimes and from national publications carried byDow Jones, can do so with a single command.andM;DataTimes, formed in 1981, is particularly noted for its collection of thefull text of major North American daily newspapers.andP;  These include theWashington Post, San Francisco Chronicle, Chicago Tribune and Seattle Times,among others, Crews said.andP;  The company recently expanded its service toinclude more wire services, trade magazines and international publications.andM;(Grant Buckler/19900703/Press Contact: Alyce Perkins, Dow Jones,609-520-4638; Wes Crews, DataTimes, 405-751-6400)</TEXT></DOC>